---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const apiEndpoint = "https://api.agent.certmate.org";
---
<Base
  title="CertMate Agent — Conversational docs for SSL certificate management"
  description="Ask anything about CertMate, ACME / Let's Encrypt, DNS-01 validation, wildcard certificates, and deploy hooks. A focused public docs assistant built on the open-source CertMate project."
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href={`${apiEndpoint}/widget/certmate-agent.css`} />
    <script type="module" src={`${apiEndpoint}/widget/certmate-agent.js`} is:inline></script>
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <h1>The conversational layer for SSL certificate ops.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      <strong>CertMate Agent</strong> answers questions about CertMate — how
      DNS-01 validation works, which DNS providers are wired in, how deploy
      hooks ship a renewed certificate to your edge, how wildcard issuance
      behaves under CNAME delegation. Read the explainers below, or just
      ask.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-row">
      <a class="btn" href="#chat">Ask the agent ↓</a>
      <a class="btn ghost" href="https://github.com/fabriziosalmi/certmate" rel="noopener">
        Self-host CertMate →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="why prose">
    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      CertMate is a self-hosted certificate manager with a small operational
      surface and a long tail of corner cases (per-provider quirks, alias
      delegation, deploy-hook contracts, ACME edge behavior). The docs cover
      them, but reading is slow. This agent searches the docs by meaning,
      cites the source, and stays grounded — it never invents features.
    </p>
    <p>
      It is built from the same codebase that self-hosters run as a sidecar
      to their own CertMate instance for live operations (renew, deploy,
      audit). Here, on the public site, it runs in <code>docs_only</code>
      mode: no live state, no write actions, just curated knowledge.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="chat" class="chat-section">
    <h2>Ask the agent</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Try: <kbd>/docs</kbd> <em>DNS-01 explained</em>, or just type a
      question.
    </p>
    <div class="widget-frame">
      <certmate-agent endpoint={apiEndpoint} fill></certmate-agent>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="topics prose">
    <h2>Curated topics</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Hand-written explainers — no LLM-generated filler. Each cites the
      CertMate source it's grounded in.
    </p>
    <ul class="topic-list">
      <li>
        <a href="/topics/what-is-certmate/">What CertMate is (and isn't)</a>
        <span class="subtle"> · Overview, scope, comparison with certbot / Traefik / Caddy</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <a href="/topics/dns-01-explained/">ACME DNS-01 challenge, end to end</a>
        <span class="subtle"> · How Let's Encrypt validates ownership via DNS, where CertMate fits</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="muted">More topics arriving — written, not generated.</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .hero {
    padding: 16px 0 32px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }
  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-top: 18px;
  }

  .why { margin-bottom: 56px; }

  .chat-section { margin: 56px 0; }
  .widget-frame {
    height: 560px;
    margin-top: 16px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    overflow: hidden;
    display: flex;
    background: var(--bg);
  }
  .widget-frame certmate-agent { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }

  .topics { margin-top: 56px; }
  .topic-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 16px 0 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 12px;
  }
  .topic-list li {
    padding: 14px 18px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    background: var(--panel);
  }
  .topic-list a {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--fg);
    border-bottom-color: var(--border-strong);
  }
</style>
